{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=September 2018}} '''Jagdish Khebudkar''' (10 May 1932 – 3 May 2011) was a [[Marathi people|Marathi]] littérateur and [[lyricist]] of [[Marathi cinema]], [[known]] for his songs in films like ''[[Pinjra (film)|Pinjra]]'' (1972), ''Sadhi Manse'', ''[[Samna (film)|Samna]]'' (1975), ''Chandra Hota Sakshila'' and ''Ashtavinayak''. Starting in 1960, he remained associated with the Marathi film industry for the next 50 years, during which he established a repertoire of 2500 songs in 300 films.<ref name="times"/><ref name=hin/> He also wrote 3500 poems, 25 stories and five plays.
==Early life and background== Born in 1932 at Haladi village District Kolhapur Maharashtra),<ref name="mirror"/> Khebudkar at the age of 16, wrote his first poem following the assassination of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] in 1948. It was aired by the [[All India Radio]].<ref name=hin>{{Cite web | title =Veteran song writer Jagdish Khebudkar passes away | url =http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/Mumbai/Veteran-song-writer-Jagdish-Khebudkar-passes-away/Article1-693117.aspx | archive-url =https://archive.is/20130803124105/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/Mumbai/Veteran-song-writer-Jagdish-Khebudkar-passes-away/Article1-693117.aspx | dead-url =yes | archive-date =3 August 2013 | publisher =Hindustan Times Mumbai, | date =4 May 2011 | accessdate =3 August 2013 }}</ref>
==Career== A teacher by profession,<ref name="mirror">{{Cite web | title = RIP Jagdish Khebudkar (1932-2011) | url = http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/RIP-Jagdish-Khebudkar-1932-2011/articleshow/16124037.cms | publisher = Mumbai Mirror | date =4 May 2011 | accessdate = 3 August 2013 }}</ref> in 1960, Khebudkar started his career as songwriter in Marathi cinema, and went on to work with noted composers like [[Ram Kadam (composer)|Ram Kadam]] and Vasant Pawar during the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name=hin/> He wrote seven songs for [[V. Shantaram]]'s Marathi hit film ''[[Pinjra (film)|Pinjra]]'' (1972), he was felicitated the V. Shantaram Lifetime Achievement Award, among others.<ref name="mirror"/> As songwriter, he wrote songs across genres, including romantic songs, religious-devotional songs and [[lavani]]s, which became popular in Marathi cinema.<ref name=hin/>
Some of his most memorable Marathi songs were written for the films Kunku Lavte Mahercha, Bijli, Don Baika Phajeeti Aika, [[Samna (film)|Samna]] and Manaacha Mujra.<ref>[http://www.dhingana.com/jagadish-khebudkar-songs-search Jagdish Khebudkar]</ref>
He died on 3 May 2011 in [[Kolhapur]] from lung infection, while being treated for [[renal ailment]]. He was cremated on the banks of Panchganga, Kolhapur. He is survived by two sons and two daughters.<ref name="times">{{Cite web | title = Marathi cinema will miss Khebudkar | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-05-05/mumbai/29511933_1_marathi-cinema-jagdish-khebudkar-songs | publisher = The Times of India | date =5 May 2011 | accessdate = 3 August 2013 }}</ref>
==Filmography== * ''Bai Mee Bholi'' (1967) * ''Bara Varshe 6 Mahine 3 Diwas'' (1967) * ''Deiva Janile Kuni'' (1967) * ''Manaacha Mujra'' (1969) * ''[[Pinjra (film)|Pinjra]]'' (1972) * ''Ghara Sansara'' (1973) * ''[[Samna (film)|Samna]]'' (1975) * ''Don Baika Phajeeti Aika'' (1982) * ''Bijli'' (1986) * ''Ashi Gyaneshwari'' (2001) * ''Navra Maza Navsacha'' (2004) * ''Kunku Lavte Mahercha'' (2004) * ''Astharoopa Jai Vaibhavlakshmi Maata'' (TV film) (2008) * ''Maherchi Maaya'' (2007)
