{{India-bio-stub}}

[[Speedruns]] are popular for a large variety of games. Most high-level speedruns have been performed by members of [[Virtual community|online communities]]. The speedrunning community originated on [[internet forum|discussion forums]] in the late 90s and early 2000s, where the fastest routes through early [[first-person shooters]] were discussed. Later-on, as speedrunning became more popular, specific video games became known as common speedrunning candidates. Some modern [[indie games]] are explicitly designed for speedrunning.

== ''Doom'' ==
{{multiple issues|
{{original research|section|date=October 2015}}
{{refimprove section|date=October 2015}}
{{outdated section|date=October 2016}}
}}
December 1993 saw the release of [[id Software|id Software's]] ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]''. Among some of its major features, like at that time unparalleled graphics, LAN- and Internet-based multiplayer support, and user modification possibilities, it also gave the players the ability to record demo files of their playthrough. This particular feature was first picked up by Christina “Strunoph” Norman in January 1994 when she launched the ''LMP Hall of Fame'' website.

This site was, however, quickly obsoleted by the ''DOOM Honorific Titles'', launched in May 1994 by Frank Stajano, which introduced the first serious competition between players.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060208154353/http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/Research/DTG/~fms27/dht/dht5/ DOOM Honorific Titles]</ref> This site would create the basis for all DOOM demosites that would follow. The DHT were designed around a notion of earning titles by successfully recording a particular type of demo on pre-determined maps in the [[IWAD]]s. These 'exams' became very popular as the player had to earn each title by sending in a demo of the feat to one of the site's judges to justify their application. Doom II was released in October 1994, and the DHT conformed to the new additions as well as the new Doom version releases. At the height of its popularity, the DHT had many different categories and playing styles. For example, playing with only the fists and pistol while killing all monsters on a map became known as Tyson mode, named after the heavyweight boxer [[Mike Tyson]]. Pacifist-mode was playing without intentionally harming any monsters. Each category had easy, medium, and hard difficulty maps for players to get randomly chosen for. Many legends in the Doom speedrunning scene started out in the DHT, including George Bell (Tyson), Steffen Udluft (Pacifist), Kai-Uwe “Gazelle” Humpert, Frank “Jesus” Siebers (Nightmare), Thomas “Panter” Pilger (Reality), and Yonatan Donner. Unfortunately, the DHT always had trouble retaining a permanent Internet location. This, combined with the changing rules and the diminished importance of most of the titles, made public interest wane as the years rolled on.

In November 1994, the Doom speedrunning scene, in the form of the COMPET-N website, took off.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doom2.net/~compet-n/index.cgi |title=C O M P E T - N |publisher=Doom2.net |date=2005-06-21 |accessdate=2013-10-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005005630/http://www.doom2.net/~compet-n/index.cgi |archivedate=2013-10-05 |df= }}</ref> Its creator, Simon Widlake, intended the site to be a record scoreboard for a variety of Doom-related achievements, but unlike its predecessors, they all centered around one key idea: speed. Players were required to run through Doom's levels as fast as humanly possible in order to attain a spot on the constantly updated COMPET-N scoreboards which eventually made Doom one of the most popular games for speedrunning.{{refn|group=Note |name=Most Popular|This statement is based on both the amount of demos and the total amount of recorded demo time, which far exceed those of other games that are popular with speedrunners.}}

Like the DOOM Honorific Titles, this site experienced multiple location changes over time; it was even at [[Simtel|Cdrom.com]] for a while before István Pataki took over as maintainer and moved the site to the now defunct FTP server [ftp://ftp.sch.bme.hu/ ftp.sch.bme.hu]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}. From there on, since early 1998, it was in the hands of Ádám Hegyi, who has been the maintainer ever since. It was located for some time at [http://www.doom2.net/ Doom2.net]. In 2012, COMPET-N player Zvonimir 'fx' Bužanić took over maintaining the site and re-created a new database for WADs and PWADs. It is currently located at http://www.doom.com.hr/compet-n.

As of March 2006, COMPET-N contains a total amount of 6072 demos (on both official and custom maps), accounting for a total time of 462 hours, 8 minutes and 20 seconds.<ref name="DoomStats">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.doom2.net/~compet-n/database/cn.cgi | title = COMPET-N Database | publisher = COMPET-N | accessdate = March 25, 2006 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060212152418/http://www.doom2.net/~compet-n/database/cn.cgi | archivedate = February 12, 2006 | df =  }}</ref>

== ''Quake'' ==
{{Multiple issues|
{{original research|section|date=October 2015}}
{{refimprove section|date=October 2015}}
{{Outdated section|date=October 2016}}
}}
''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]'' was the only game to rival ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' as the most popular game to speedrun.{{refn|group=Note |name=Most Popular}} People first started recording demos of ''Quake'' playthroughs when it was released in June 1996 and sharing them with others on the <tt>demos/e</tt> directory in [[Simtel|Cdrom.com]]'s ''Quake'' file hierarchy. There were two distinct kinds of demos: those in which the player killed all monsters and found all secrets on the map (called 100% demos) and those in which the player ignored these goals in order to finish the level as fast as possible (called runs). All levels were, at that time, recorded solely on the “Nightmare” difficulty level, the highest in the game.

In April 1997, Nolan “Radix” Pflug first started the Nightmare Speed Demos web site to keep track of the fastest demos. The first ''[[Quake Done Quick]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetquake.com/QdQ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060114082242/http://www.planetquake.com/qdq/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2006-01-14 |title=Quake done Quick |publisher=Wayback.archive.org |date=2006-03-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04 |df= }}</ref> of the game, carrying over one level's finishing statistics to the next. The run ended up finishing the entire game on Nightmare difficulty in 0:19:49;<ref name=autogenerated4>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090131110937/http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/qdqr.html Quake Done Quick: QdQr]</ref> an astonishing feat at that time. It received widespread attention from gaming magazines, being distributed with free [[Compact disc|CDs]] that usually came with them. This popularized speedrunning for a much larger audience than before and attracted many newcomers. Not all of those newcomers agreed with the old-timers's dogma that runs should be made on the hardest possible skill level. Thus, in August 1997 Muad'Dib's ''Quake'' Page came to be, run by Gunnar “Muad'Dib” Andre Mo and specializing in “Easy” difficulty runs. One month after that, the famous ''Quake Done Quick'' movie was superseded by a new movie called ''Quake Done Quicker'', on September 14, 1997, which improved the game's fastest playthrough time to 0:16:35.<ref name=autogenerated4 />

In April 1998, Nolan and Gunnar merged their pages, thus creating [[Speed Demos Archive]], which today is still the central repository for ''Quake'' speed demos of any kind. Ever since its creation, a large variety of tricks have been discovered in the ''Quake'' physics, which kept players interested even up to today, more than two decades after Quake's release. Subsequently, ''[[Quake Done Quick|Quake Done Quick with a Vengeance]]'' was released on September 13, 2000, which featured a complete run through ''Quake'' in the hugely improved time of 0:12:23.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/qdqwav.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415034604/http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/qdqwav.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2009-04-15  |title=Quake Done Quick: QdQwav |publisher=Wayback.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>

As of March 2006, Speed Demos Archive contains a total amount of 8481 demos (on both official and custom maps), accounting for a total time of 253 hours, 44 minutes and 39 seconds.<ref name="QuakeStats">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = https://archive.org/details/Quake_SDA_collection | title = Quake (PC) - Speed demo collection | publisher = Internet Archive | accessdate = March 25, 2006 }}</ref> The fastest minimalist single-segment completion times that have been recorded thus far, as of June 10, 2006, are 0:13:46<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://speeddemosarchive.com/quake/demos/ER/all_1346.dz Downloadable demo]</ref> for the easy difficulty run and 0:19:50<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://speeddemosarchive.com/quake/demos/NR/all_1950.dz Downloadable demo]</ref> for the nightmare difficulty run, both by long-time ''Quake'' speedrunner Connor Fitzgerald. The 100% single-segment completion times are 0:46:02 <ref name=autogenerated1>[http://speeddemosarchive.com/quake/demos/EH/all_4602.dz Downloadable demo]</ref> for the easy difficulty run and 1:09:33 for the nightmare difficulty run, respectively Marlo Galinski and Justin Fleck.{{refn|group=Note |name=Quake demos|''Quake'' demos are usually stored in the Dzip compression algorithm, which was developed by Nolan Pflug and Stefan Schwoon. It is available for free download at [http://speeddemosarchive.com/dzip/download.html Dzip Online].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://speeddemosarchive.com/dzip/|website=speeddemosarchive.com|title=Dzip Online}}</ref>}}

=== ''Quake Done Quick'' ===
{{Main|Quake Done Quick}}
An important aspect of the ''Quake'' speedrunning community is ''[[Quake Done Quick]]'', a collection of movies in which the game is finished as fast as possible with special rules and aims. Unlike the normal records listed above, these movies are created one level at a time rather than in one continuous play session; as such, it is possible for multiple people to help create the movie by sending in demos of individual levels, and much faster times can be aimed for as the segmentation allows one to easily try again upon committing an error. It also allows runners to only have to focus on a small portion of the game rather than all of it.

These movies are by far more popular than the conventional records, both in the community itself and outside of it. Some of them, most notably the movies that feature a fast playthrough of the game on the Nightmare difficulty level without additional voluntary challenges, have even been distributed with gaming magazines and posted on news sites. [[Slashdot]] has published an announcement of the then newly created ''Quake Done Quick with a Vengeance'' movie on its front page.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://games.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=00/09/14/1223230&tid=112 |title=Slashdot &#124; Quake Done Quick - With A Vengeance |publisher=Games.slashdot.org |date=2000-09-14 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> Out of all the series' movies, this one is also the most popular. In it, the entire game is finished in 0:12:23 on “Nightmare” difficulty, the hardest in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/qdqwav.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221161546/http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/qdqwav.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2009-02-21  |title=Quake Done Quick: QdQwav |publisher=Wayback.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> This run succeeded ''Quake Done Quicker'' and the original ''Quake done Quick'' <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090131110937/http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/qdqr.html ]</ref> movie, in which the game was finished in respectively 0:16:35 and 0:19:49.<ref name="QuakeDoneQuicker">{{cite web | year = 1997 | url = http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/all_1635.txt| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080103145316/http://qdq.planetquake.gamespy.com/all_1635.txt | dead-url = yes | archive-date = January 3, 2008  | title = Quake done Quicker | publisher = Quake done Quick | author = The Quake done Quick team | accessdate = December 25, 2005 }}</ref> The main reason for the latest installment being over 4 minutes faster, an improvement that surpassed the initial expectations of the runners,<ref name="SequenceBreakingExample">{{cite web|year=2006 |url=http://www.fileplanet.com/dl/dl.asp?qdq/qdqwav.dz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204054530/http://www.fileplanet.com/dl/dl.asp?qdq%2Fqdqwav.dz |dead-url=yes |archive-date=February 4, 2012 |title=History of the routes in QdQwav |publisher=FilePlanet |author=The Quake done Quick team |accessdate=March 26, 2006 |df= }}</ref> was the discovery of [[bunny hopping]], which allowed runners to attain a much higher speed in most levels and even made it possible to save rockets or grenades for jumps that could now be done without them.<ref name="BunnyHopReference">See the [[Speedrun#Techniques 2|Quake Techniques]] paragraph.</ref> This movie is currently being improved by new and old runners for a production called ''Quake done Quick with a Vengeance Part II''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://speeddemosarchive.com/quake/projects/qdqwavp2/ |title=Quake done Quickest |publisher=Speeddemosarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> As of May 2006, the improvements that have been made thus far would result in a time of 0:11:32 for the entire game, an improvement of 51 seconds.<ref name="QuakeDoneQuickWithAVengeancePartIIProgress">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://speeddemosarchive.com/quake/projects/qdqwavp2/tables.html | title = Quake done Quick with a Vengeance Part II | publisher = Speed Demos Archive | author = Speed Demos Archive contributors | accessdate = May 7, 2006 }}</ref>

Some of the productions have been turned into [[Machinima]] movies, using so-called “recams” (showing the run from preset camera perspectives rather than the first-person view) and sometimes even custom skins, models, and a script to turn them into [[film]]s rather than speedrun videos.

== ''Metroid'' series ==
''[[Super Metroid]]'' (Nintendo, 1994) achieved popularity with speedrunners due to the emergence of console emulators with demo-recording features.<ref name=1up>{{cite web|url = http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3142599&did=1|title = Smashing the Clock|publisher = 1UP.com| last=Turner|first=Benjamin |date=2005-08-10|accessdate = August 13, 2005 }}</ref> In normal ''Super Metroid'' gameplay, the player may find certain items such as "high-jump boots". Since the path through the map is non-linear, it is complicated to find the most efficient speedrunning routes: areas with seemingly essential power-ups can be bypassed at the expense of the improved mobility. This drove the discovery of [[sequence breaking]], in which a player can acquire power-ups before the game design intends, allowing whole sections of the map to be skipped.<ref name=1up/> As of September 2018 the current Any%{{refn|group=Note |name=Any|"Any%" refers to beating a game without having to play through any optional content, and, in Super Metroid's case, without the use of major glitches.}} world record is held by speedrunner Behemoth, with a time of 41 minutes and 18 seconds.

Because the ''Metroid'' series awards players for completing the game with a faster time, groups of player were inspired to discuss techniques on message boards such as [[GameFAQs]] and to capture and post video of full playthroughs. Despite internet limitations in the early 2000s, the ability to share video footage of ''Metroid'' runs allowed speedrunners to collaborate and learn from one another.<ref name="Bad Jump">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2013/10/zelda-wind-waker-speedrun/|publisher=''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''|title=For the World’s Fastest Gamers, Failure Is Just One Bad Jump Away|last=Rigney|first=Ryan|date=2013-10-16}}</ref> It was during online discussions of ''[[Metroid Prime]]'' that the term "sequence breaking" was first widely used.<ref name="Polygon money">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/features/2014/1/9/5280786/making-money-zelda-speed-runner|publisher=''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''|title=Making money as a Zelda speed runner|last=Li|first=Roland|date=2014-01-09}}</ref>

== ''Super Mario'' series ==
[[File:Super_Mario_World_arbitrary_code_injection.jpg|thumb|left|By injecting [[arbitrary code execution|arbitrary code]] into the memory of ''[[Super Mario World]]'' in the form of [[video game sprite|graphical sprites]], speedrunners can reprogram the entire game on the fly.<ref name="PC MAG arbitrary code" /><ref name="Ars" />]]
{{see also|List of Super Mario speedrunning records}}

Early [[platform games]] of the ''[[Super Mario]]'' series are popular in the speedrunning community. ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', ''[[Super Mario World]]'', ''[[Yoshi's Island]]'' and ''[[Super Mario 64]]'' are particularly notable for speedrunning accomplishments. Most notable speedruns of ''Super Mario'' games are generally carried out without [[Tool-assisted speedrun|tool-assistance]], though speedrunners make frequent use of [[video game glitch|glitches]] and even [[memory corruption]] to make optimal times.

The current record holder of the first game in the ''Super Mario'' series, ''Super Mario Bros.'', is speedrunner somewes, who beat the game in 4 minutes, 55 seconds, and 796 milliseconds on October 22, 2018. This was done by using many frame-perfect tricks and in-game warps. More novel achievements have also been accomplished in ''Super Mario Bros.'', such as beating the game with the [[Score (game)#Video games|lowest score possible]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/guy-beats-super-mario-bros-with-the-lowest-score-possib-1526905435|publisher=''Kotaku''|title=Guy Beats Super Mario Bros. With The Lowest Score Possible|last=Person|first=Chris|date=2014-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/gammasquad/2014/02/watch-lowest-scoring-super-mario-bros-speedrun-ever/|publisher=''[[Uproxx]]''|title=Watch The Lowest Scoring ‘Super Mario Bros.’ Speedrun Ever|last=Seitz|first=Dan|date=2014-02-20}}</ref>

The record-time for beating ''Super Mario World'' is in the hands of speedrunner FURiOUS,<ref>{{cite web |title=Super Mario World Leaderboard |url=https://www.speedrun.com/smw#0_Exit |website=speedrun.com |accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref> who beat the game in 41 seconds and 866 milliseconds on June 19, 2018. This was done by making the credits of the game roll using [[arbitrary code execution|arbitrary code injection]] in the first level of the game, however this is not considered an entirely fair way of beating the game, and is best done using tool-assistance.<ref name="PC MAG arbitrary code">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2475640,00.asp|publisher=''PC Magazine''|title=Speedrunner 'Beats' Super Mario World in Under 5 Minutes|last=Murphy|first=David|date=2015-01-22}}</ref><ref name="Ars">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2014/01/how-an-emulator-fueled-robot-reprogrammed-super-mario-world-on-the-fly/|publisher=''Ars Technica''|title=How an emulator-fueled robot reprogrammed Super Mario World on the fly|last=Orland|first=Kyle|date=2014-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.extremetech.com/extreme/174659-super-mario-world-speedrun-hack-takes-up-up-down-down-left-right-left-right-b-a-to-the-next-level|publisher=''ExtremeTech''|title=Super Mario World speedrun hack takes up up down down left right left right B A to the next level|last=Anthony|first=Sebastian|date=2014-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/01/22/super-mario-world-record-_n_6522082.html|publisher=''The Huffington Post''|title='Super Mario World' Speedrun Record Smashed Using Bizarre Glitch|last=Rundle|first=Michael|date=2015-01-22}}</ref>

''Super Mario World 2: Yoshi's Island'' is a game that is very commonly speedrun at [[Awesome Games Done Quick]]. Charlie Hall of ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' has described speedruns of ''Yoshi's Island'' as a "great introduction to the showmanship and the rich community" behind the Games Done Quick marathons. Through exchanging strategies and doing theory routing, the ''Yoshi's Island'' speedrunning community collaboratively work on pushing the time down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/why-speed-running-is-the-greatest-thing-about-gaming-729|publisher=''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]''|title=Why Speed-Running Is the Greatest Thing About Gaming|last=Whelan|first=David|date=2015-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/7/27/9047665/sgdq-trihex-yoshis-island-2015|publisher=''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''|title=SGDQ's first run shows off the skill, community that makes it all possible|last=Hall|first=Charlie|date=2015-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/02/05/twitch-tv-speedrun-interview/|publisher=''VentureBeat''|title=Can live speedruns compete with e-sports? (interview)|last=Haley|first=Sebastian|date=2013-02-05}}</ref>

It is possible to speedrun ''Super Mario 64'' in various ways. Though speedruns exist of people playing through the game as intended, it is possible to skip large portions of ''Super Mario 64'' by using glitches. Using a glitch dubbed the "backwards long jump," with which the [[player character]] can move through walls, a player can skip almost all levels of the game and beat it in only a few minutes.<ref name="Bad Jump" /><ref name="Nintendo Glitches">{{cite web|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/arts/5-nintendo-games-you-can-beat-in-minutes-because-of-glitches-6387128|publisher=''[[Houston Press]]''|title=5 Nintendo games you can beat in minutes because of glitches|last=Rouner|first=Jeff|date=2014-10-14}}</ref> Completing ''Super Mario 64'' 100%—i.e., collecting all the game's "stars"—is also a popular method of playing through the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geek.com/games/super-mario-64-speedrun-world-record-accidentally-broken-1616736/|publisher=''Geek''|title=Super Mario 64 speedrun world record accidentally broken|last=Humphries|first=Matthew|date=2015-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/guy-breaks-super-mario-64-world-record-by-accident-1688469992|publisher=''Kotaku''|title=Race Leads To New World Record For Collecting 120 Super Mario 64 Stars|last=Hernandez|first=Patricia|date=2015-02-27}}</ref> Recently, the 120 Stars category has become much more competitive. The current record time for Super Mario 64 in the "120 Stars" category was set on February 8, 2018 by the Twitch streamer Cheese05 with a time of 1 hour, 39 minutes, and 19 seconds.

== ''The Legend of Zelda'' series ==
{{see also|List of The Legend of Zelda speedrunning records}}
The [[The Legend of Zelda (video game)|original ''The Legend of Zelda'']] and ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time]]'' are popular speedrunning candidates. The record for the first game in the series is currently held by speedrunner LackAttack24 in 28 minutes and 37 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twitch.tv/videos/165262422?t=02s|title=(28:37) The Legend of Zelda - any% no up+a (current world record)|last=|first=|date=2017-07-08|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Any%{{refn|group=Note |name=Any}} speedruns of this game involve a great deal of movement optimization and item drop management, as well as some amount of luck. Speedrunners rely heavily on having bombs with which to defeat high-level enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeldainformer.com/news/new-legend-of-zelda-nes-speedrun-world-record-first-sub-30-minute-run|publisher=''Zelda Informer''|title=New NES Legend of Zelda Speedrun World Record, First Sub-30 Minute Run|last=Lloyd|first=Rod|date=2015-04-04}}</ref> A common glitch used in speedruns of this game involves [[clipping (computer graphics)|clipping]] through walls while the screen is scrolling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/the-original-legend-of-zelda-beaten-in-30-minutes-a-ne-1681817617|publisher=''Kotaku''|title=The Original Legend of Zelda Beaten In 30 Minutes, A New World Record|last=Hernandez|first=Patricia|date=2015-01-26}}</ref>

The original Japanese version of ''[[The Legend of Zelda: A Link to the Past]]'', the third game in the series, can be beaten within two minutes by using particularly advantageous glitches. However, this workaround was patched in subsequent versions of the game, including the US and PAL release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/10/video_learn_how_to_clear_the_legend_of_zelda_a_link_to_the_past_in_under_two_minutes|publisher=''[[Nintendo Life]]''|title=Video: Learn How to Clear The Legend of Zelda: A Link to the Past in Under Two Minutes|last=Whitehead|first=Thomas|date=2015-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.se/articles/2015-10-03-sahar-klarar-du-the-legend-of-zelda-a-link-to-the-past-pa-under-2-min|publisher=''[[Eurogamer]]'' Sweden|title=Såhär klarar du The Legend of Zelda: A Link to the Past på under 2 min|last=Petterson|first=Alex|date=2015-10-03}}</ref>

[[File:Speedrun Ocarina of Time - Team Superplay - Mang'Azur 2013 - P1590514.jpg|thumb|right|A speedrun of ''Ocarina of Time'' being carried out at [[Mang'Azur festival]] in 2013.]]

===''The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time''===

''Ocarina of Time'' speedruns used to take hours to carry out, as the game contains a large amount of long, mandatory dungeons. During the 2000s, the community of Speed Demo Archives discovered various glitches in the game that allowed players to skip portions of it. The "Door of Time Skip", for instance, allows player character [[Link (character)|Link]] to sequence break and skip many of the game's levels by passing through a wall. In 2012, the "Wrong Warp" glitch was discovered, which allowed Link to [[warp (gaming)|teleport]] from the first dungeon to the final boss of the game, making 20 minute speedruns of ''Ocarina of Time'' possible.<ref name="Polygon money" />

Speedruns of ''Ocarina of Time'' are somewhat dependent of the [[video game console|console]] the game is played on. Originally, speedrunners played ''Ocarina of Time'' on the Chinese-only [[iQue Player]], because it has quicker loading times and faster scrolling text than the [[Nintendo 64]] version. However, the current record was achieved with the Japanese version of ''Ocarina of Time'' played on the [[Wii Virtual Console]], as this version of the game includes an exploitable glitch not present in other versions.<ref name="Gamerant Ocarina">{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/world-record-ocarina-of-time-speedrun-skater82297/|publisher=''Gamerant''|title=Gamer Sets New World Record for ‘Ocarina of Time’ Speedrun|last=Gates|first=Christopher|date=2015-05-09}}</ref>

''The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time'' has been described as "one of the most intricate and well-documented games for speed running" because of its familiarity and potential for glitches.<ref name="Polygon money" /> The current any% world record is in hands of skater82297, with a time of 17 minutes and 07 seconds, beating Torje's previous record of 17 minutes and 09 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.speedrun.com/oot|publisher=''Speedrun.com''|title=Ocarina of Time|date=2018-03-17}}</ref> The current 100% world record is held at a time of 3 hours 53 minutes and 33 seconds, which belongs to American runner Zfg, who has held the 100% speedrun world record since March 19, 2015 and had previously become the first person to complete the 100% run in under 4 hours, doing so on August 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.speedrun.com/oot#100|title=The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time - Leaderboard - speedrun.com|last=|first=|date=|website=speedrun.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/8/3/17649600/zelda-ocarina-of-time-speedrun-100-percent-world-record|title=Ocarina of Time speedrunner breaks four-hour barrier for a 100% run (Corrected)|work=Polygon|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2018/08/its-been-a-groundbreaking-month-for-ocarina-of-time-speedrunning/|title=It's Been A Groundbreaking Month For Ocarina Of Time Speedrunning|date=2018-08-25|work=Kotaku Australia|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref>

==''Dark Souls'' series==
''[[Dark Souls]]'', a 2011 game by [[From Software]], is known for its unforgiving gameplay, but despite this, the game is very popular among speedrunners. Through the use of several intricate skips, glitches, and wrong warps, it is possible to complete an Any%{{refn|group=Note |name=Any}} run in under 35 minutes, though average players take dozens of hours playing through the game once.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5966725/watch-this-speed-run-take-down-dark-souls-in-32-minutes|publisher=''Kotaku''|title=Watch This Speed Run Take Down Dark Souls in 32 Minutes|last=Narcisse|first=Evan|date=2012-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/dark-souls-speed-run-record-completes-the-game-in-less-than-50-minutes/|publisher=''PC Gamer''|title=Dark Souls speed run record completes the game in less than 50 minutes |last=Presscot|first=Shaun|date=2015-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/01/19/dark-souls-how-long-does-it-take-to-beat-speed-run-record/|publisher=''[[VG247]]''|title=Dark Souls beaten in less than 50 minutes in new speed run record|last=Hillier|first=Brenna|date=2015-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/10/16/dark-souls-speed-run-is-a-tour-de-force-of-tolerance/|publisher=''[[Engadget]]''|title=Dark Souls speed run is a tour de force of tolerance|last=Mallory|first=Jordan|date=2011-10-16}}</ref> 21-minute speedruns are possible because of a glitch dubbed the "Kiln Skip", which can be used to skip almost the entire second half of the game. The original method for this exploit was removed in an update,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/12/18/dark-souls-speedrun/|publisher=''VentureBeat''|title=Guinness World Record holder breaks down his half-hour Dark Souls speedrun (interview)|last=Haley|first=Sebastian|date=2012-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-01-19-watch-dark-souls-completed-in-under-50-minutes|publisher=''Eurogamer''|title= Watch Dark Souls completed in under 50 minutes|last=Matulef|first=Jeffrey|date=2015-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2015/01/man-breaks-dark-souls-speed-run-world-record-still-thinks-he-sucks/|publisher=''kotaku Australia''|title=Man Breaks Dark Souls World Record, Still Thinks He Sucks|last=Serrels|first=Mark|date=2015-01-19}}</ref> but a new method of performing it, which requires the current game update, has also been devised. The current world record for the All Bosses category speedrun is held by CapitaineToinon, clocking in at 1:09:02 IGT (in-game time).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://speedsouls.com/darksouls:All_Bosses|title=All Bosses - Speed Souls - A Dark Souls Speedrunning Wiki|website=speedsouls.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>

Any% runs of its sequel, ''[[Dark Souls II]]'', can be done in under 20 minutes, as it is possible to avoid almost all battles in the game and to move around the world at a "ridiculous pace" using the "binoculars" item. The tricks that make a run this short possible were patched out, but can still be used if current patches aren't downloaded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dark-souls-2-completed-in-20-minutes/1100-6420071/|publisher=''[[GameSpot]]''|title=Dark Souls 2 Completed in 20 Minutes|last=Newhouse|first=Alex|date=2014-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/6/3/5775250/dark-souls-2-speed-run|publisher=''Polygon''|title=This Dark Souls 2 player can speed run through the game in 20 minutes|last=Gera|first=Emily|date=2014-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/it-s-possible-to-beat-dark-souls-ii-in-20-minutes-275813.phtml|publisher=''Destructoid''|title=It's possible to beat Dark Souls II in 20 minutes|last=Devore|first=Jordan|date=2014-06-02}}</ref>

==''Spelunky''==
''[[Spelunky]]'', a 2012 indie [[platform game|platformer]] created by [[Derek Yu]], has been a common candidate for speedrunning, with its fastest runs taking between one and two minutes. As ''Spelunky'' features a large amount of random [[procedural generation]], speedrunners cannot solely rely on memorization. To have a chance in beating the current record, a speedrunner must get a specific [[random seed]], though despite this, skillful players may recognize repeating level patterns and know how to optimally use the game's items, such as a difficult to use "teleporter" that allows a player to skip large chunks of a level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-07-spelunky-speedrun-world-record-set-at-1-47-182|publisher=''[[Eurogamer]]''|title=Spelunky speedrun world record set at 1:47.182|last=Matulef|first=Jeffrey|date=2015-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-07-14-spelunky-speed-run-sets-new-world-record|publisher=''Eurogamer''|title=Spelunky speed run sets new world record|last=Matulef|first=Jeffrey|date=2014-07-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/8/18/9171939/watch-spelunky-beaten-in-101-seconds-in-a-world-record-speed-run|publisher=''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''|title=Watch Spelunky beaten in 101 seconds in a world record speed run|last=Kuchera|first=Ben|date=2015-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/spelunky-world-record-speedrun-looks-like-magic-1703102779|publisher=''Kotaku''|title=Spelunky World Record Speedrun Looks Like Magic|last=Klepek|first=Patrick|date=2015-05-08}}</ref>

Despite the high difficulty of the game, even ''Spelunky''{{'s}} "Hell" levels have been used for speedrunning, with the world record sitting under four minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/8/13/9150207/spelunky-speedrun-hell-world-record-3-minutes-44-seconds|publisher=''Polygon''|title=See someone finish Spelunky in less time than it takes us to make a sandwich|last=Kollar|first=Philip|date=2015-09-13}}</ref> Another highly difficult run of the game is the so-called "[[eggplant run]]", in which a player has to go through a specific set of objectives to turn the final boss into an [[eggplant]]. This was done [[single-player game|solo]] for the first time in November 2013 by speedrunner [[Bananasaurus Rex]], though it took him 90 minutes. Douglas Wilson of ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' dubbed this run "2013's most fascinating video game moment."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/spelunkys-first-solo-eggplant-run-completed-makes-for-a-tense-hour-of-platforming/|publisher=''PC Gamer''|title=Spelunky's first solo eggplant run completed, makes for a tense hour of platforming|last=Morrison|first=Angus|date=2013-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/11/11/5093020/spelunky-eggplant-run-video|publisher=''Polygon''|title=Spelunky player achieves the elusive solo Eggplant Run|last=Tach|first=Dave|date=2013-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/12/23/5227726/anatomy-of-a-spelunky-miracle-or-how-the-internet-finally-beat|publisher=''Polygon''|title=A breakdown of 2013's most fascinating video game moment|last=Wilson|first=Douglas|date=2013-12-23}}</ref>

