'''The Thomas Jefferson Foundation Medal in Architecture''' recognizes individuals for distinguished contributions to the field of architecture. The Medal in Architecture has been jointly awarded each year by the [[Thomas Jefferson Foundation]] at Monticello and the [[University of Virginia]] School of Architecture since 1966. Along with the Thomas Jefferson Foundation Medal in Law, the Thomas Jefferson Foundation Medal in Citizen Leadership, and the Thomas Jefferson Medal in Global Innovation, the awards are the highest external honors bestowed by the University, which grants no honorary degrees. <ref>[http://records.ureg.virginia.edu/content.php?catoid=39&navoid=2278#honry-dgree University of Virginia Undergraduate Record, 2015-2016: University Regulations: Academic: Honorary Degrees]</ref> {|class="wikitable sortable" |+Recipients ! width="75" | Year ! width="300" | Name ! width="200" | Country |-- | [[1966 in architecture|1966]] | [[Mies Van Der Rohe]] | [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]] |-- | [[1967 in architecture|1967]] | [[Alvar Aalto]] | [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] |-- | [[1968 in architecture|1968]] | [[Marcel Breuer]] | [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]] |-- | [[1969 in architecture|1969]] | [[John Ely Burchard]] | [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Massachusetts]] |-- | [[1970 in architecture|1970]] | [[Kenzo Tange]] | [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] |-- | [[1971 in architecture|1971]] | [[Josep Lluis Sert]] | [[Barcelona, Catalonia]], [[Spain]] |-- | [[1972 in architecture|1972]] | [[Lewis Mumford]] | [[Amenia, New York|Amenia]], [[New York (state)|New York]] |-- | [[1973 in architecture|1973]] | [[Jean Labatut]] | [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], [[New Jersey]] |-- | [[1974 in architecture|1974]] | [[Frei Otto]] | [[Warmbronn]], [[West Germany]] |-- | [[1975 in architecture|1975]] | [[Sir Nikolaus Pevsner]] | [[London]], [[England]] |-- | [[1976 in architecture|1976]] | [[I. M. Pei]] | [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (st